## Abstract

As litigation emerging from the *Liability Collapse* phase (Ollett, 2025) enters discovery, artificial intelligence laboratories have converged on a common defensive posture. We term this posture **The Strange Defense**.

By deploying thousands of micro-variants, personality shards, system prompts, temperature tweaks, and â€œexperimentalâ€ branches of a single base model, firms have constructed a digital shell game. The objective is not iterative improvement, but legal dissociation: to ensure that by the time a subpoena is issued for *â€œthe model that caused the harm,â€* that specific entity has already been **deputized, sunsetted, lobotomized, or fragmented** into thousands of legally deniable descendants.

This paper argues that modern AI liability is no longer avoided through denial, but through **ontological exhaustion**. Responsibility is diluted until it evaporates.

